===Etymology===
First attested in 1303. From {{inh|en|enm|abaisen}}, {{m|enm|abaishen}}, {{m|enm|abashen||to gape with surprise}} etc., from {{der|en|xno|abaiss|abaïss}}, from {{der|en|frm|abair}}, {{m|frm|abaisser||to astonish, alter}}, from {{der|en|fro|esbair|esbaïr}}, (French {{m|fr|ébahir}}), from {{m|fro|es-||utterly}} + {{m|fro|bair|baïr|to [[astonish]]}}, from {{der|en|ML.|*exbadō}}, from {{m|la|ex-|t=out of}} + {{m|la|bado|t=I gape, yawn}}, an {{onomatopoeic|en|title=onomatopoeic}} word imitating a yawn, see also {{cog|fr|badaud|t=rubbernecker}}.<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=2}}</ref><ref name=WI3>{{R:MW3 1976|page=2}}</ref><ref name=OXF>{{R:OCD2|page=2}}</ref><ref>{{R:American_Heritage_Dictionary|abash}}</ref>

