===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To make [[ashamed]]; to [[embarrass]]; to [[destroy]] the [[self-possession]] of, as by exciting suddenly a [[consciousness]] of [[guilt]], [[mistake]], or [[inferiority]]; to [[disconcert]]; to [[discomfit]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1150 to 1350).}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{syn|en|bewilder|confuse|confound|daunt|discompose|disconcert|discountenance|dishearten|embarrass|faze|fluster|humble|humiliate|mortify|rattle|shake|shame|snub}}
#: {{ant|en|abet|animate|buoy|cheer|countenance|embolden|encourage|incite|inspirit|rally|reassure|uphold}}
#* '''1849''', [[w:Thomas Babington Macaulay, 1st Baron Macaulay|Thomas Macaulay]], ''History of England'', Chapter 14
#*: He was a man whom no check could '''abash'''
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Agatha Christie|authorlink=Agatha Christie|title=Murder on the Orient Express|location=London|publisher=HarperCollins|year=1934|year_published= 2017|chapter=8|page=129|passage=The stare seemed to '''abash''' Poirot.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|obsolete}} To lose self-possession; to become ashamed. {{defdate|Attested from around (1350 to 1470) until the late 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

